    "abstract": "<jats:title>Summary</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  A significant number of COVID-19 patients develop \u2018long COVID\u2019, a condition defined by long-lasting debilitating, often neurological, symptoms. The pathophysiology of long COVID is unknown. Here we present\n                  <jats:italic>in-vivo</jats:italic>\n                  evidence of widespread neuroinflammation in long COVID, using a quantitative assessment, [\n                  <jats:sup>18</jats:sup>\n                  F]DPA-714 PET, in two long COVID patients. We reanalyzed historical data from three matched healthy control subjects, for comparison purposes. Both patients with long COVID had widespread increases in [\n                  <jats:sup>18</jats:sup>\n                  F]DPA-714 binding throughout the brain. Quantitative measures of binding (BP\n                  <jats:sub>ND</jats:sub>\n                  values) were increased on average by 121% and 76%, respectively. This implicates profound neuroinflammation in the pathophysiology of long COVID.\n                </jats:p>",
